For this problem, we will be using the concept of the future value annuity. The future value annuity refers to the future value of the recurring payments based on the given rates and time. It can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Future value annuity}&=\text{Payment}\times\dfrac{(1+\frac{\text{rate}}{\text{number of times compounded}})^\text{time}-1}{\frac{\text{rate}}{\text{number of times compounded}}}
\end{aligned}$$

Now, we will solve for the payment that we need to achieve an annual return of $9.7\%$ after 40 years. Since we will use the time in months, then we will use $\text{time}=40\times12=480$. Substituting the values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\$1,000,000&=\text{Payment}\times\dfrac{(1+\frac{0.097}{12})^{480}-1}{\frac{0.097}{12}}
\end{aligned}$$
